give small example in C++ how its useful "Now only 2 elements stored instead of 9".

Let’s make this concrete with a **small C++ example** that shows *why storing only 2 elements is useful*.

---

## ❌ Normal (dense) matrix — wastes space

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int mat[3][3] = {
        {0, 0, 5},
        {0, 0, 0},
        {0, 3, 0}
    };

    // Print matrix
    for(int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
        for(int j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
            cout << mat[i][j] << " ";
        }
        cout << endl;
    }
}
```

👉 Problem:

* Stores **9 integers**
* But only **2 are useful**

---

## ✅ Sparse version — stores only useful data

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;

struct Element {
    int row, col, value;
};

int main() {
    vector<Element> sparse = {
        {0, 2, 5},
        {2, 1, 3}
    };

    int rows = 3, cols = 3;

    // Reconstruct and print full matrix
    for(int i = 0; i < rows; i++) {
        for(int j = 0; j < cols; j++) {
            int val = 0;

            // Check if (i,j) exists in sparse list
            for(auto &e : sparse) {
                if(e.row == i && e.col == j) {
                    val = e.value;
                    break;
                }
            }

            cout << val << " ";
        }
        cout << endl;
    }
}
```

---

## 🎯 Why this is useful

### 1. Memory saving

* Dense → 9 integers
* Sparse → only 2 elements (each has 3 ints, but still better for large matrices)

👉 Imagine **1000×1000 matrix with only 10 values**

* Dense → 1,000,000 elements
* Sparse → just 10 stored

---

### 2. Faster operations (real benefit)

If you want to **sum all values**:

#### Dense:

```cpp
// checks all 9 elements
for(i,j) sum += mat[i][j];
```

#### Sparse:

```cpp
// only 2 elements
for(auto &e : sparse) sum += e.value;
```

👉 Less loops = faster

---

### 3. Real-world usage

* Graphs (store only connections)
* Game maps (mostly empty space)
* Scientific computing
* Search engines / ML sparse data

---

## ⚡ Key takeaway

> You don’t store zeros because they carry no information —
> you store only what matters and *infer the rest as zero*

